%I A376924 #133 Jun 04 2026 19:15:23
%S A376924 4375,8750,13125,17500,21875,26250,30625,35000,39375,43750,3136,52500,
%T A376924 1728,61250,65625,70000,5120,78750,6144,87500,91875,6272,2048,105000,
%U A376924 109375,3456,118125,122500,2430,131250,4000,140000,9408,10240,153125,157500,32805,12288,5184,175000
%N A376924 a(n) is the largest number such that both a(n) and a(n) - n are 7-smooth numbers, or 0 if no such number exists.
%C A376924 From _Zhicheng Wei_, May 26 2026: (Start)
%C A376924 All terms n>1 are currently conjectural.
%C A376924 a(1) is just A002072(4) + 1, which is proven by Størmer's theorem. This provides a(n) is not zero where n is 7-smooth. All other terms are conjectured, but the abc-conjecture can help.
%C A376924 a(n) can be less than n and this first occurs at a(1849) = 1800 because there is no answer to >1849. 1800 = 2^3 * 3^2 * 5^2 and 1800-1849 = -49 = -(7^2). Here we also consider negative numbers as smooth numbers. (End)
%F A376924 If a(n) or a(p*n) exists then a(p*n) >= p * a(n) for p in {2, 3, 5, 7}. - _Zhicheng Wei_, May 26 2026
%e A376924 a(31) = 4000 since both 4000 and 4000 - 31 = 3969 are 7-smooth numbers, and it is conjectured that no number k larger than 4000 such that both k and k - 31 are 7-smooth numbers.
%o A376924 (PARI)
%o A376924 M(v, u, lim)={vecsort(concat(vector(#v, i, my(m=lim\v[i]); v[i]*select(t->t<=m, u))))}
%o A376924 Gen(lim, k)={my(v=[1]); forprime(p=2, k, v=M(v, vector(logint(lim, p)+1, e, p^(e-1)), lim)); v}
%o A376924 lista(n, lim=10^30)={my(v=vector(n), G=Gen(lim, 7)); for(i=1, #G, my(t=G[i], k=i+1); while(k<=#G && G[k]-t<=n, v[G[k]-t]=G[k]; k++)); v} \\ _Andrew Howroyd_, Oct 11 2024
%o A376924 (PARI)
%o A376924 A006530(n)=if(n>1, vecmax(factor(n)[, 1]), 1)
%o A376924 b(n)=for(t=1, n, A006530(t*(n-t))<=7&return(t))
%o A376924 A376924(n)=if(lista(n)[n]!=0, return(lista(n)[n]); lista(n)[n]==0&b(n)<n, return(n-b(n)); lista(n)[n]==0&b(n)==n, return(0)) \\ _Zhicheng Wei_, May 26 2026
%Y A376924 Cf. A002072, A002473, A106600.
%K A376924 nonn,changed
